    <itunes:author>Craig Peterson</itunes:author>
    <itunes:subtitle>Jon Grodem the Sr. Director of Product and Marketing at Optoma joins Craig at CES to discuss DLP® projectors. With mobile devices (iPods, smart phones, tablets, gaming devices, etc) having taken the world by storm, Optoma has led the charge in developing </itunes:subtitle>
    <description>&lt;p&gt;Jon Grodem the Sr. Director of Product and Marketing at Optoma joins Craig at CES to discuss DLP&amp;reg; projectors. With mobile devices (iPods, smart phones, tablets, gaming devices, etc) having taken the world by storm, Optoma has led the charge in developing personal, mobile and portable projectors to complement this movement. At CES, Optoma will unveil two new projectors, both of which offer connectivity to almost all mobile devices.  The PK320 is a 100-lumen, 8 oz., pocket-sized Pico projector that can project widescreen images up to 150&amp;#8221; It not only connects to any device, (computers, tablets, smart phones, gaming consoles, or digital cameras and camcorders), but it also has a microSD card slot (up to 32GB) and on-board Office Viewer software that allow users to see Microsoft Office files (word, PowerPoint, Excel, etc.), as well as most common image formats, in their native form without the need for PC.  Otoma&amp;#8217;s all new ML300 represents the company&amp;#8217;s second offering in the &amp;#8220;mobile&amp;#8221; projector category. At 1.4 lbs and measuring a sleek 7.2&amp;rdquo; x 1.8&amp;rdquo; x 4.4&amp;rdquo;, it fits easily into any briefcase or handbag. Yet its performance belies its small size. &lt;/p&gt;</description>
    <itunes:summary>Jon Grodem the Sr. Director of Product and Marketing at Optoma joins Craig at CES to discuss DLP® projectors. With mobile devices (iPods, smart phones, tablets, gaming devices, etc) having taken the world by storm, Optoma has led the charge in developing personal, mobile and portable projectors to complement this movement. At CES, Optoma will unveil two new projectors, both of which offer connectivity to almost all mobile devices.  The PK320 is a 100-lumen, 8 oz., pocket-sized Pico projector that can project widescreen images up to 150" It not only connects to any device, (computers, tablets, smart phones, gaming consoles, or digital cameras and camcorders), but it also has a microSD card slot (up to 32GB) and on-board Office Viewer software that allow users to see Microsoft Office files (word, PowerPoint, Excel, etc.), as well as most common image formats, in their native form without the need for PC.  Otoma&apos;s all new ML300 represents the company&apos;s second offering in the "mobile" projector category. At 1.4 lbs and measuring a sleek 7.2 x 1.8 x 4.4, it fits easily into any briefcase or handbag. Yet its performance belies its small size.</itunes:summary>
