    <itunes:subtitle>Dennis Peng the CMO at Ooma joins Craig on the floor at CES to discuss a breakthrough technology that is transforming the landscape of consumer telephony. There is so much wrong with phone service today it&apos;s pricey, limited, and inflexible - and we m</itunes:subtitle>
    <description>&lt;p&gt;Dennis Peng the CMO at Ooma joins Craig on the floor at CES to discuss a breakthrough technology that is transforming the landscape of consumer telephony. There is so much wrong with phone service today it&amp;#8217;s pricey, limited, and inflexible &amp;#8211; and we made it our mission to create a better customer phoning experience. Ooma, Inc., the leading provider of HD-quality free home phone service, today announced a new cordless handset with superior HD Voice call clarity and smartphone features made possible by the Ooma cloud-enabled platform.  Ooma customers can save even more money on their mobile calling plan by tapping into their Ooma account on the go and making phone calls over any Wi-Fi or 3G network with the Ooma Mobile HD app. The Ooma Mobile HD app is compatible with Android devices as well as the iPhone, iPod Touch and iPad. It costs $9.99 to download from app stores. The combination of the Ooma Telo and new Ooma HD2 Handset provides cutting-edge HD Voice call clarity by capturing twice the voice data to double the fidelity of standard phone calls, for richer, more natural-sounding conversations. Immediately following this interview Craig will be joined by Jim Bak the Director of Community Relations at Inrix.  They will discuss real-time traffic information and connected driving services in the car, online and on mobile devices. INRIX&apos;s traffic intelligence platform is fueled by the world&apos;s largest community of drivers. Through sophisticated analysis of real-time data from 50 million vehicles and hundreds of public and private sources, INRIX knows the best routes and keeps drivers moving with real-time updates on changes to conditions along the way.  Traffic congestion costs us $100 billion last year, nearly $750 for every commuter or 34 hours per year stuck in traffic for the average commuter. At CES, we&apos;re introducing new intelligent driving services with Ford and JVC that integrate consumer&apos;s own mobile devices with in-car systems for delivering traffic information that makes driving easier everyday.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
